ine\">\\(0\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{4}{18}\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(2\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\((U,V)=(-1,-2)\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\((U,V)=(1,2)\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"even\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{1}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{6}{18}\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>On obtient ainsi la loi du couple <span class=\"math inline\">\\((U,V)\\)</span>:</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"header\">\n<th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(X \\backslash Y\\)</span></th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(-2\\)</span></th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(1\\)</span></th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(2\\)</span></th>\n<th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\prob_U\\)</span> (loi de <span class=\"math inline\">\\(U\\)</span>)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(-1\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{1}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{2}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{3}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{6}{18}\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"even\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(1\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{2}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{4}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{6}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{12}{18}\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\prob_V\\)</span> (loi de <span class=\"math inline\">\\(V\\)</span>)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{3}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{6}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(\\frac{9}{18}\\)</span></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"math inline\">\\(1\\)</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>On peut vérifier que: <span class=\"math display\">\\[\\forall i\\in\\{-1,1\\}, \\forall j\\in\\{-2,1,2\\}, \\quad \\prob(U=i,V=j)=\\prob(U=i)\\times \\prob(V=j)\\]</span> donc les variables aléatoires <span class=\"math inline\">\\(U\\)</span> et <span class=\"math inline\">\\(V\\)</span> sont indépendantes.</p>\n"
